'''Herschel''' is a 304 kilometer [[Impact crater|Impact Basin]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Herschel Impact Basin, Mars | author= Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum | url=http://airandspace.si.edu/explore-and-learn/multimedia/detail.cfm?id=6082}}</ref> in the Martian southern hemisphere, at 14.5°S, 130°E, located in the [[Mare Tyrrhenum quadrangle|Mare Tyrrhenum]] region<ref>{{cite web|title=Analysis of Diverse Dune Fields in Herschel Crater (Mars)from HiRISE Datasets | author=M. Cardinale, G. Komatsu, International Research School of Planetary Sciences | url=http://meetingorganizer.copernicus.org/EPSC2010/EPSC2010-155.pdf}}</ref> of [[Mars]] and is inside [[Terra Cimmeria]]. The crater is jointly named after the seventeenth/eighteenth century father and son [[astronomer]]s [[William Herschel]] and [[John Herschel]].<ref>{{cite web|title=John Frederick William Herschel (March 7, 1792 - May 11, 1871) | url=http://messier.seds.org/xtra/Bios/jherschel.html}}</ref>

[[File:PSP 002860 1650 RED.browse.jpg|thumb|upright=2.0|200px|left|Dark dunes in Hershel crater.]]
Nearby named craters include the much smaller Luqa to the southeast, also further south is the slightly smaller [[Müller (Martian crater)|Müller]], to the north is the slightly smaller [[Knobel (Martian crater)|Knobel]] and [[Robert Sharp (crater)|Robert Sharp]] craters and northeast are the [[Lasswitz (crater)|Lasswitz]]-[[Wien (crater)|Wien]] crater pair.

== Moving Sand Dunes ==

[[Mars Global Surveyor]] spacecraft originally photographed fields of dark [[sand dune]]s within Herschel.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dark Dunes in Herschel Crater|author=NASA/JPL/University of Arizona | url=http://hiroc.lpl.arizona.edu/images/PSP/diafotizo.php?ID=PSP_002860_1650}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dark Sand Dunes and Sand Sheet in Herschel Crater|author=NASA/JPL/University of Arizona | url=http://www.uahirise.org/PSP_010257_1655}}</ref> Images from the [[NASA]] [[Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter]] showed that sand dunes on the floor of the Herschel crater are not stationary (as previously believed), but moved over time. Images from photos taken by the Orbiter's [[High Resolution Imaging Science Experiment]] (HiRISE) on March 3, 2007 and December 1, 2010 show clear shifting of dunes and ripples.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rippling Dune Front in Herschel Crater on Mars|author=NASA/JPL-Caltech/Univ. of Ariz./JHUAPL| url=http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/MRO/multimedia/pia14879.html}}</ref>  Research published in Icarus stated that the dunes in Hershel Crater moved  0.8 m  in a time span of 3.7 Earth-years. Also, it was determined that dune ripple moved 1.1 m in that time period.<ref>Cardinale, M., S. Silvestro,  D. Vazd, T.  Michaels, M. Bourke, G. Komatsu, L.  Marinangeli.  2016.  Present-day aeolian activity in Herschel Crater, Mars.  Icarus: 265, 139-148.</ref>

